# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcohol-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcohol-chemistry/al] In chemistry, the suffix **-al** is the IUPAC nomenclature used in organic chemistry to form names of aldehydes containing the -(CO)H group in the systematic form.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/al] It was extracted from the word "aldehyde".
[src:alcohol-chemistry/al] With the exception of chemical compounds having a higher priority than it, all aldehydes are named using -al, such as 'propanal'.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/al] Some aldehydes also have common names, such as formaldehyde for methanal, acetaldehyde for ethanal.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/al] Benzaldehyde does not have a systematic form with -al.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In chemistry, an **alcohol** (from Arabic *al-kuḥl* 'the kohl') is a type of organic compound that carries at least one hydroxyl (−OH) functional group bound to a saturated carbon atom.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols range from the simple, like methanol and ethanol, to complex, like sugar alcohols and cholesterol.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The presence of an OH group strongly modifies the properties of hydrocarbons, conferring hydrophilic (water-attracted) properties.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The OH group provides a site at which many reactions can occur.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The flammable nature of the exhalations of wine was already known to ancient natural philosophers such as Aristotle (384–322 BCE), Theophrastus (c.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] However, this did not immediately lead to the isolation of alcohol, even despite the development of more advanced distillation techniques in second- and third-century Roman Egypt.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] An important recognition, first found in one of the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (ninth century CE), was that by adding salt to boiling wine, which increases the wine's relative volatility, the flammability of the resulting vapors may be enhanced.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In the twelfth century, recipes for the production of *aqua ardens* ("burning water", i.e., alcohol) by distilling wine with salt started to appear in a number of Latin works, and by the end of the thirteenth century, it had become a widely known substance among Western European chemists.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still, by which an alcohol purity of 90% could be obtained.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The medicinal properties of ethanol were studied by Arnald of Villanova (1240–1311 CE) and John of Rupescissa (c.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] 1310–1366), the latter of whom regarded it as a life-preserving substance able to prevent all diseases (the *aqua vitae* or "water of life", also called by John the *quintessence* of wine).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The word "alcohol" derives from the Arabic *kohl* (Arabic: الكحل, romanized: *al-kuḥl*), a powder used as an eyeliner.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The first part of the word (*al-*) is the Arabic definite article, equivalent to *the* in English.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The second part of the word (*kuḥl*) has several antecedents in Semitic languages, ultimately deriving from the Akkadian 𒎎𒋆𒁉𒍣𒁕 (*guḫlum*), meaning stibnite or antimony.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Like its antecedents in Arabic and older languages, the term *alcohol* was originally used for the very fine powder produced by the sublimation of the natural mineral stibnite to form antimony trisulfide Sb2S3.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] It was considered to be the essence or "spirit" of this mineral.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] It was used as an antiseptic, eyeliner, and cosmetic.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Later the meaning of alcohol was extended to distilled substances in general, and then narrowed again to ethanol, when "spirits" was a synonym for hard liquor.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Paracelsus and Libavius both used the term *alcohol* to denote a fine powder, the latter speaking of an *alcohol* derived from antimony.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] At the same time Paracelsus uses the word for a volatile liquid; *alcool* or *alcool vini* occurs often in his writings.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The 1657 *Lexicon Chymicum* by William Johnson glosses the word as "antimonium sive stibium." By extension, the word came to refer to any fluid obtained by distillation, including "alcohol of wine," the distilled essence of wine.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Libavius in *Alchymia* (1594) refers to "vini alcohol vel vinum alcalisatum".
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The term *ethanol* was invented in 1892, blending "ethane" with the "-ol" ending of "alcohol", which was generalized as a libfix.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The term *alcohol* originally referred to the primary alcohol ethanol (ethyl alcohol), which is used as a drug and is the main alcohol present in alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* appears in the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) chemical name of all substances where the hydroxyl group is the functional group with the highest priority.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] When a higher priority group is present in the compound, the prefix *hydroxy-* is used in its IUPAC name.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* in non-IUPAC names (such as paracetamol or cholesterol) also typically indicates that the substance is an alcohol.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] However, some compounds that contain hydroxyl functional groups have *trivial names* that do not include the suffix *-ol* or the prefix *hydroxy-*, e.g. the sugars glucose and sucrose.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] IUPAC nomenclature is used in scientific publications, and in writings where precise identification of the substance is important.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In naming simple alcohols, the name of the alkane chain loses the terminal *e* and adds the suffix *-ol*, *e.g.*, as in "ethanol" from the alkane chain name "ethane".
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] When necessary, the position of the hydroxyl group is indicated by a number between the alkane name and the *-ol*: propan-1-ol for CH3CH2CH2OH, propan-2-ol for CH3CH(OH)CH3.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] If a higher priority group is present (such as an aldehyde, ketone, or carboxylic acid), then the prefix *hydroxy-*is used, e.g., as in 1-hydroxy-2-propanone (CH3C(O)CH2OH).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Compounds having more than one hydroxy group are called polyols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] They are named using suffixes -diol, -triol, etc., following a list of the position numbers of the hydroxyl groups, as in propane-1,2-diol for CH3CH(OH)CH2OH (propylene glycol).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In cases where the hydroxy group is bonded to an sp2 carbon on an aromatic ring, the molecule is classified separately as a phenol and is named using the IUPAC rules for naming phenols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Phenols have distinct properties and are not classified as alcohols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In other less formal contexts, an alcohol is often called with the name of the corresponding alkyl group followed by the word "alcohol", e.g., methyl alcohol, ethyl alcohol.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Propyl alcohol may be *n*-propyl alcohol or isopropyl alcohol, depending on whether the hydroxyl group is bonded to the end or middle carbon on the straight propane chain.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] As described under systematic naming, if another group on the molecule takes priority, the alcohol moiety is often indicated using the "hydroxy-" prefix.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In archaic nomenclature, alcohols can be named as derivatives of methanol using "-carbinol" as the ending.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] For instance, (CH3)3COH can be named trimethylcarbinol.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols are then classified into primary, secondary (*sec-*, *s-*), and tertiary (*tert-*, *t-*), based upon the number of carbon atoms connected to the carbon atom that bears the hydroxyl functional group.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The respective numeric shorthands 1°, 2°, and 3° are sometimes used in informal settings.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The primary alcohols have general formulas RCH2OH.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest primary alcohol is methanol (CH3OH), for which R = H, and the next is ethanol, for which R = CH3, the methyl group.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary alcohols are those of the form RR'CHOH, the simplest of which is 2-propanol (R = R' = CH3).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] For the tertiary alcohols, the general form is RR'R"COH.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest example is *tert*-butanol (2-methylpropan-2-ol), for which each of R, R', and R" is CH3.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In these shorthands, R, R', and R" represent substituents, alkyl or other attached, generally organic groups.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols have a long history of myriad uses.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol is the most common industrial alcohol, with about 12 million tons/y produced in 1980.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The combined capacity of the other alcohols is about the same, distributed roughly equally.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] With respect to acute toxicity, simple alcohols have low acute toxicities.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Doses of several milliliters are tolerated.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] For pentanols, hexanols, octanols, and longer alcohols, LD50 range from 2–5 g/kg (rats, oral).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol and ethylene glycol are more toxic than other simple alcohols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Their metabolism is affected by the presence of ethanol, which has a higher affinity for liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In this way, methanol will be excreted intact in urine.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In general, the hydroxyl group makes alcohols polar.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Those groups can form hydrogen bonds to one another and to most other compounds.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Owing to the presence of the polar OH alcohols are more water-soluble than simple hydrocarbons.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol, ethanol, and propanol are miscible in water.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] 1-Butanol, with a four-carbon chain, is moderately soluble.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Because of hydrogen bonding, alcohols tend to have higher boiling points than comparable hydrocarbons and ethers.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The boiling point of the alcohol ethanol is 78.29 °C, compared to 69 °C for the hydrocarbon hexane, and 34.6 °C for diethyl ether.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols occur widely in nature, as derivatives of glucose such as cellulose and hemicellulose, and in phenols and their derivatives such as lignin.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Starting from biomass, 180 billion tons/y of complex carbohydrates (sugar polymers) are produced commercially (as of 2014).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Many other alcohols are pervasive in organisms, as manifested in other sugars such as fructose and sucrose, in polyols such as glycerol, and in some amino acids such as serine.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Simple alcohols like methanol, ethanol, and propanol occur in modest quantities in nature, and are industrially synthesized in large quantities for use as chemical precursors, fuels, and solvents.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Many alcohols are produced by hydroxylation, i.e., the installation of a hydroxy group using oxygen or a related oxidant.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Hydroxylation is the means by which the body processes many poisons, converting lipophilic compounds into hydrophilic derivatives that are more readily excreted.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Enzymes called hydroxylases and oxidases facilitate these conversions.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Many industrial alcohols, such as cyclohexanol for the production of nylon, are produced by hydroxylation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In the Ziegler process, linear alcohols are produced from ethylene and triethylaluminium followed by oxidation and hydrolysis.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The process generates a range of alcohols that are separated by distillation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Many higher alcohols are produced by hydroformylation of alkenes followed by hydrogenation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Such processes give fatty alcohols, which are useful for detergents.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Industry produces low-weight molecular alcohols (e.g. ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, and *tert*-butanol) through the acid-catalyzed hydration of alkenes, the latter typically from cracking fractions of distilled crude oil.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Two implementations are employed: the direct and indirect methods.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In the indirect method, the alkene is converted to a sulfate ester, which is subsequently hydrolyzed.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The direct method eschews intermediates, instead using water to quench an intermediate carbocation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Less aggressive reagents suffice for vicinal difunctionalization.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In industry, the diol ethylene glycol forms when ethylene oxide is hydrolyzed.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In the laboratory, sulfuric acid also catalyzes hydration of alkenes to secondary or tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] More controllable net hydrations proceed in multiple steps, with a vicinally-functionalized intermediate.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Thus oxymercuration initially forms an organomercury alcohol, which can then undergo reductive demetalation; and alkenes react with *N*-bromosuccinimide and water to form halohydrins.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In hydroboration-oxidation and the related Mukaiyama hydration, an alkene is hydrometalated, then oxidized.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Ethanol is obtained by fermentation of glucose (which is often obtained from starch) in the presence of yeast.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Like ethanol, butanol can be produced by fermentation processes.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] *Saccharomyces* yeast are known to produce these higher alcohols at temperatures above 75 °F (24 °C).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The bacterium *Clostridium acetobutylicum* can feed on cellulose (also an alcohol) to produce butanol on an industrial scale.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alkyl halides react with aqueous NaOH or KOH to give alcohols in nucleophilic aliphatic substitution.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary and especially tertiary alkyl halides will give the elimination (alkene) product instead.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Grignard reagents react with carbonyl groups to give secondary and tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Related reactions are the Barbier reaction and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Aldehydes or ketones are reduced with sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride (after an acidic workup).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Another reduction using aluminium isopropoxide is the Meerwein–Ponndorf–Verley reduction.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation is the asymmetric reduction of β-keto-esters.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] With aqueous p*K*a values of around 16–19, alcohols are, in general, slightly weaker acids than water.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] With strong bases such as sodium hydride or sodium they form salts called *alkoxides*, with the general formula RO−M+ (where R is an alkyl and M is a metal).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The acidity of alcohols is strongly affected by solvation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In the gas phase, alcohols are more acidic than in water.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In DMSO, alcohols (and water) have a p*K*a of around 29–32.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] As a consequence, alkoxides (and hydroxide) are powerful bases and nucleophiles (e.g., for the Williamson ether synthesis) in this solvent.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In particular, RO− or HO− in DMSO can be used to generate significant equilibrium concentrations of acetylide ions through the deprotonation of alkynes (see Favorskii reaction).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with hydrochloric acid to produce tertiary alkyl chloride.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Primary and secondary alcohols are converted to the corresponding chlorides using thionyl chloride and various phosphorus chloride reagents.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] In the Barton–McCombie deoxygenation an alcohol is deoxygenated to an alkane with tributyltin hydride or a trimethylborane-water complex in a radical substitution reaction.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Meanwhile, the oxygen atom has lone pairs of nonbonded electrons that render it weakly basic in the presence of strong acids such as sulfuric acid.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Upon treatment with strong acids, alcohols undergo the E1 elimination reaction to produce alkenes.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction, in general, obeys Zaytsev's rule, which states that the most stable (usually the most substituted) alkene is formed.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols are eliminated easily at just above room temperature, but primary alcohols require a higher temperature.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] A more controlled elimination reaction requires the formation of the xanthate ester.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with strong acids to generate carbocations.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction is related to their dehydration, e.g. isobutylene from *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] A special kind of dehydration reaction involves triphenylmethanol and especially its amine-substituted derivatives.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] When treated with acid, these alcohols lose water to give stable carbocations, which are commercial dyes.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohol and carboxylic acids react in the so-called Fischer esterification.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Other types of ester are prepared in a similar manner−for example, tosyl (tosylate) esters are made by reaction of the alcohol with 4-toluenesulfonyl chloride in pyridine.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alcohols (R−CH2OH) can be oxidized either to aldehydes (R−CHO) or to carboxylic acids (R−CO2H).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The oxidation of secondary alcohols (R1R2CH−OH) normally terminates at the ketone (R1R2C=O) stage.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols (R1R2R3C−OH) are resistant to oxidation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids normally proceeds via the corresponding aldehyde, which is transformed via an *aldehyde hydrate* (R−CH(OH)2) by reaction with water before it can be further oxidized to the carboxylic acid.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] Reagents useful for the transformation of primary alcohols to aldehydes are normally also suitable for the oxidation of secondary alcohols to ketones.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] These include Collins reagent and Dess–Martin periodinane.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids can be carried out using potassium permanganate or the Jones reagent.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ane] In organic chemistry, the suffix ***-ane*** forms the names of organic compounds where the −C−C− group (a carbon-carbon single bond) has been attributed the highest priority according to the rules of organic nomenclature.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ane] Such organic compounds are called *alkanes*.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ane] The names of the saturated hydrides of non-metals end with the suffix ***-ane***: the hydrides of silicon are called silanes (SiH4); the hydrides of boron are boranes (B2H6).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ane] The final "*-e*" is dropped before a suffix that starts with a vowel, e.g.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ane] Alternatively, "*-ane*" may be used for a mononuclear hydride of an element.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ane] For instance, methane for CH4 and oxidane for H2O (water).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ase] The suffix **-ase** is used in biochemistry to form names of enzymes.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ase] The most common way to name enzymes is to add this suffix onto the end of the substrate, *e.g.* an enzyme that breaks down peroxides may be called peroxidase; the enzyme that produces telomeres is called telomerase.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ase] Sometimes enzymes are named for the function they perform, rather than substrate, e.g. the enzyme that polymerizes (assembles) DNA into strands is called polymerase; see also reverse transcriptase.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ase] The *-ase* suffix is a libfix derived from "diastase", the first recognized enzyme.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ase] Its usage in subsequently discovered enzymes was proposed by Émile Duclaux, with the intention of honoring the first scientists to isolate diastase.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] The suffix **-ene** is used in organic chemistry to form names of organic compounds where the -C=C- group has been attributed the highest priority according to the rules of organic nomenclature.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] Sometimes a number between hyphens is inserted before it to say that the double bond is between that atom and the atom with the next number up.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] This suffix is taken from the end of the word ethylene, which is the simplest alkene.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] The final "-e" disappears if it is followed by a suffix that starts with a vowel, e.g.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] "-enal" which is a compound that contains both a -C=C- bond and an aldehyde functional group.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] A Greek number prefix before the "-ene" indicates how many double bonds there are in the compound, e.g. butadiene.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] The suffix "-ene" is also used in inorganic chemistry to indicate a one-atom thick two-dimensional layer of atoms—known as a "Xene"—as in graphene, silicene, stanene, borophene, and germanene.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ene] Additionally, the suffixis used for MXenes due to their similarity to graphene.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] *asinine, canine, feline, ursine*), the suffix is usually pronounced /aɪn/ or in some words alternatively /ɪn/.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] *Levantine, Byzantine, Argentine*) it is usually /aɪn/ or /iːn/.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] But in chemistry, it is usually pronounced /iːn/ or /ɪn/ depending on the word it appears in and the accent of the speaker.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] In a few words (for example, *quinine*, *iodine* and *strychnine*), the /aɪn/ sound is normal in some accents.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] *Gasoline* ends with /iːn/; *glycerine* more often with /ɪn/ than with /iːn/.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] In *caffeine*, the suffix has merged with the *e* in the root, for stressed /ˈiːn/; in *gasoline* and *margarine* as well the suffix is stressed by some people.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] Some elements of the periodic table (namely the halogens, in the Group 17) have this suffix: fluorine (F), chlorine (Cl), bromine (Br), iodine (I) and astatine (At), ending which was continued in the artificially created tennessine (Ts).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] The suffix *-in* (/ɪn/) is etymologically related and overlaps in usage with *-ine*.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/ine] Many proteins and lipids have names ending with *-in*: for example, the enzymes pepsin and trypsin, the hormones insulin and gastrin, and the lipids stearin (stearine) and olein.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oate] The suffix **-oate** is the IUPAC nomenclature used in organic chemistry to form names of compounds formed with ester.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oate] The most common examples of compounds named with the "oate" suffix are esters, like ethyl acetate, CH 3COOCH 2CH 3.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] In organic chemistry, a **carboxylic acid** is a polar, organic acid that contains a **carboxyl group** (−C(=O)−OH) attached to an R-group.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The general formula of a carboxylic acid is often written as **R−COOH** or **R−CO2H**, sometimes as R−C(O)OH, with R referring to an organyl group (e.g., alkyl, alkenyl, aryl), or hydrogen, or other groups.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Important examples include the amino acids and fatty acids.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Deprotonation of a carboxylic acid gives a carboxylate anion.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are often considered weak acids as they only partially ionise (dissociate) in water.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are commonly identified by their trivial names.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] IUPAC-recommended names also exist; in this system, carboxylic acids have an *-oic acid* suffix.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For example, butyric acid (CH3CH2CH2CO2H) is butanoic acid by IUPAC guidelines.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For nomenclature of complex molecules containing a carboxylic acid, the carboxyl can be considered position one of the parent chain even if there are other substituents, such as 3-chloropropanoic acid.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Alternately, it can be named as a "carboxy" or "carboxylic acid" substituent on another parent structure, such as 2-carboxyfuran.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The carboxylate anion (R−COO− or R−CO−2) of a carboxylic acid is usually named with the suffix *-ate*, in keeping with the general pattern of *-ic acid* and *-ate* for a conjugate acid and its conjugate base, respectively.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For example, the conjugate base of acetic acid is acetate.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carbonic acid, which occurs in bicarbonate buffer systems in nature, is not generally classed as one of the carboxylic acids, despite it having a moiety that looks like a COOH group.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Because they are both hydrogen-bond acceptors (the carbonyl −C(=O)−) and hydrogen-bond donors (the hydroxyl −OH), they also participate in hydrogen bonding.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Together, the hydroxyl and carbonyl group form the functional group carboxyl.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids usually exist as dimers in nonpolar media due to their tendency to "self-associate".
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Smaller carboxylic acids (1 to 5 carbons) are soluble in water, whereas bigger carboxylic acids have limited solubility due to the increasing hydrophobic nature of the alkyl chain.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] These longer chain acids tend to be soluble in less-polar solvents such as ethers and alcohols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Aqueous sodium hydroxide and carboxylic acids, even hydrophobic ones, react to yield water-soluble sodium salts.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For example, enanthic acid has a low solubility in water (0.2 g/L), but its sodium salt is very soluble in water.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids tend to have higher boiling points than water, because of their greater surface areas and their tendency to form stabilized dimers through hydrogen bonds.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For boiling to occur, either the dimer bonds must be broken or the entire dimer arrangement must be vaporized, increasing the enthalpy of vaporization requirements significantly.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are Brønsted–Lowry acids because they are proton (H+) donors.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] They are the most common type of organic acid.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are typically weak acids, meaning that they only partially dissociate into [H3O]+ cations and R−CO−2 anions in neutral aqueous solution.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For example, at room temperature, in a 1-molar solution of acetic acid, only 0.001% of the acid are dissociated (i.e.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Electron-withdrawing substituents such as trifluoromethyl (−CF3) give stronger acids (the p*K*a of acetic acid is 4.76 whereas trifluoroacetic acid, with a trifluoromethyl substituent, has a p*K*a of 0.23).
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Deprotonation of carboxylic acids gives carboxylate anions; these are resonance stabilized, because the negative charge is delocalized over the two oxygen atoms, increasing the stability of the anion.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Each of the carbon–oxygen bonds in the carboxylate anion has a partial double-bond character.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The carbonyl carbon's partial positive charge is also weakened by the −1/2 negative charges on the 2 oxygen atoms.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids often have strong sour odours.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Esters of carboxylic acids tend to have fruity, pleasant odours, and many are used in perfume.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are readily identified as such by infrared spectroscopy.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] They exhibit a sharp band associated with vibration of the C=O carbonyl bond (*ν*C=O) between 1680 and 1725 cm−1.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] A characteristic *ν*O–H band appears as a broad peak in the 2500 to 3000 cm−1 region.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] By 1H NMR spectrometry, the hydroxyl hydrogen appears in the 10–13 ppm region, although it is often either broadened or not observed owing to exchange with traces of water.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Many carboxylic acids are produced industrially on a large scale.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] They are also frequently found in nature.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Esters of fatty acids are the main components of lipids and polyamides of aminocarboxylic acids are the main components of proteins.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are used in the production of polymers, pharmaceuticals, solvents, and food additives.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase (aka RuBisCo), the most abundant protein, catalyzes the carbonation to give carboxylic acids.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] This conversion is the carbon-fixation step in photosynthesis.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Routes to other biologically prevalent carboxylic acids - citric, oxalic, amino acids, etc. - entail hydrolysis of thioesters and phosphate esters.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] In contrast to methods used on a laboratory scale, industrial routes to carboxylic acids often require specialized equipment for high pressures and high temperatures.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Preparative methods for small scale reactions for research or for production of fine chemicals often employ expensive consumable reagents.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Many reactions produce carboxylic acids but are used only in specific cases or are mainly of academic interest.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids react with bases to form carboxylate salts, in which the hydrogen of the hydroxyl (–OH) group is replaced with a metal cation.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Widely practiced reactions convert carboxylic acids into esters, amides, carboxylate salts, acid chlorides, and alcohols.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Their conversion to esters is widely used, e.g. in the production of polyesters.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Likewise, carboxylic acids are converted into amides, but this conversion typically does not occur by direct reaction of the carboxylic acid and the amine.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Instead esters are typical precursors to amides.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The conversion of amino acids into peptides is a significant biochemical process that requires ATP.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Converting a carboxylic acid to an amide is possible, but not straightforward.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Instead of acting as a nucleophile, an amine will react as a base in the presence of a carboxylic acid to give the ammonium carboxylate salt.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Heating the salt to above 100 °C will drive off water and lead to the formation of the amide.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] This method of synthesizing amides is industrially important, and has laboratory applications as well.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] In the presence of a strong acid catalyst, carboxylic acids can condense to form acid anhydrides.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The condensation produces water, however, which can hydrolyze the anhydride back to the starting carboxylic acids.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Thus, the formation of the anhydride via condensation is an equilibrium process.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Under acid-catalyzed conditions, carboxylic acids will react with alcohols to form esters via the Fischer esterification reaction, which is also an equilibrium process.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Alternatively, diazomethane can be used to convert an acid to an ester.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] While esterification reactions with diazomethane often give quantitative yields, diazomethane is only useful for forming methyl esters.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Like esters, most carboxylic acids can be reduced to alcohols by hydrogenation, or using hydride transferring agents such as lithium aluminium hydride.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Strong alkyl transferring agents, such as organolithium compounds but not Grignard reagents, will reduce carboxylic acids to ketones along with transfer of the alkyl group.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The Vilsmaier reagent (*N*,*N*-Dimethyl(chloromethylene)ammonium chloride; [ClHC=N+(CH3)2]Cl−) is a highly chemoselective agent for carboxylic acid reduction.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] It selectively activates the carboxylic acid to give the carboxymethyleneammonium salt, which can be reduced by a mild reductant like lithium tris(*t*-butoxy)aluminum hydride to afford an aldehyde in a one pot procedure.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] This procedure is known to tolerate reactive carbonyl functionalities such as ketone as well as moderately reactive ester, olefin, nitrile, and halide moieties.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The hydroxyl group on carboxylic acids may be replaced with a chlorine atom using thionyl chloride to give acyl chlorides.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] In nature, carboxylic acids are converted to thioesters.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Thionyl chloride can be used to convert carboxylic acids to their corresponding acyl chlorides.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] First, carboxylic acid **1** attacks thionyl chloride, and chloride ion leaves.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The resulting oxonium ion **2** is activated towards nucleophilic attack and has a good leaving group, setting it apart from a normal carboxylic acid.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] In the next step, **2** is attacked by chloride ion to give tetrahedral intermediate **3**, a chlorosulfite.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The tetrahedral intermediate collapses with the loss of sulfur dioxide and chloride ion, giving protonated acyl chloride **4**.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Chloride ion can remove the proton on the carbonyl group, giving the acyl chloride **5** with a loss of HCl.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Phosphorus(III) chloride (PCl3) and phosphorus(V) chloride (PCl5) will also convert carboxylic acids to acid chlorides, by a similar mechanism.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] One equivalent of PCl3 can react with three equivalents of acid, producing one equivalent of H3PO3, or phosphorus acid, in addition to the desired acid chloride.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] PCl5 reacts with carboxylic acids in a 1:1 ratio, and produces phosphorus(V) oxychloride (POCl3) and hydrogen chloride (HCl) as byproducts.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids react with Grignard reagents and organolithiums to form ketones.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The first equivalent of nucleophile acts as a base and deprotonates the acid.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] A second equivalent will attack the carbonyl group to create a geminal alkoxide dianion, which is protonated upon workup to give the hydrate of a ketone.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] Because most ketone hydrates are unstable relative to their corresponding ketones, the equilibrium between the two is shifted heavily in favor of the ketone.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] For example, the equilibrium constant for the formation of acetone hydrate from acetone is only 0.002.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The carboxylic group is the most acidic in organic compounds.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The carboxyl radical, •COOH, only exists briefly.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The acid dissociation constant of •COOH has been measured using electron paramagnetic resonance spectroscopy.
[src:alcohol-chemistry/oic-acid] The carboxyl group tends to dimerise to form oxalic acid.
